Case Study:¶

To create a classifier that can be implemented easily on streaming sensor data to detect Shake gesture¶

Datasets:¶

Data from three types of sensors(a, m and l) are used for the analysis. Each sensor has two datasets sensor.csv and lbl.csv. are given with below feature:

Sensor.csv has data phone sensors recorded every 100 ms (10Hz frequency).

  • timestamp(ms) : Unix Timestamp in milliseconds.
  • acceleration_x(g) : Acceleration along phone's x axis (measured in g)
  • acceleration_y(g) : Acceleration along phone's y axis (measured in g)
  • acceleration_z(g) : Acceleration along phone's z axis (measured in g)
  • roll(rad) : Roll angle representing phone's attitude (orientation)
  • pitch(rad) : Pitch angle representing phone's attitude (orientation)
  • yaw(rad) : Yaw angle representing phone's attitude (orientation)
  • angular_velocity_x(rad/sec) : Angular velocity around x axis (passing thru phones center along smaller edge)
  • angular_velocity_y(rad/sec) : Angular velocity around y axis (passing thru phones center along longer edge)
  • angular_velocity_z(rad/sec) : Angular velocity around z axis (passing thru phones center emerging out of phone )

lbl.csv contains 2 types of labels with time interval:

  • Label 0 : Represents start of Shake gesture
  • Label 1 : Indicates end of Shake gesture

Approch Overview:¶

  • MasterData Preparation: Lables has been mapped to sensor data based on the timestamp interval.
  • Performed descriptive analysis:
    • Box Plot for outlier detection
    • Pair plots to understand the relationship between all the features
    • Correlation matrix
  • Models: Post feature engineering below models were developed
    • Logistic Regression
    • Decision Tree
    • Random Forest
    • XGBoost

Model Observations:¶

Refer each Model section

Recomendation:¶

Based on F1 score: Random Forest model is best with trainF1Score : 0.62 and testF1Score : 0.50

def data_info(df):
    # Basic health check of data
    # args: 
        # df : dataset
    # return: dataset
    df_info = pd.DataFrame(df.isna().sum(),columns = ['Null_count'])
    df_info['Non_Null_count'] = df_info.index.map(df.notna().sum())
    df_info['N_unique'] = df_info.index.map(df.nunique())
    df_info['D_types'] = df_info.index.map(df.dtypes)
    df_info['Blank_count'] = df_info.index.map((df=='').sum())
    return df_info
In [4]:
def rem_xsd_more(data_col,th=3):
    # Function to tag observation as outlier based on predefined threshold in terms of standard deviations
    # args: 
        # data_col: data columns
        # th: standard deviation as threshold
    # returns: True if outlier , False if non-outlier 
    mean = data_col.mean()
    std = data_col.std()
    return((data_col-mean)/std>th)
In [5]:
def rem_xpctl_more(data_col,pctl_th=0.99):
    # Function to tag observation as outlier based on predefined threshold in terms of quantile
    # args: 
        # data_col: data columns
        # th: percentile as threshold
    # returns: True if outlier , False if non-outlier 
    pctl = data_col.quantile(pctl_th)
    return data_col>pctl

Feature Engineering¶

In [24]:
base.head(1)

0 1396948626717 0.0008 0.0038 -0.0054 -0.0217 0.0018 0.0 -0.001 -0.001 -0.0014 m 0.0 m 1396949162159
Calculating features which represent change in radian per unit metre i.e angular_acceleration/acceleration for each axis where angular_acceleration = angular_velocity / time(100ms) as the data is collected every 100ms¶
As value is very small, so multiplying it by 10000¶
In [25]:
base['rad_per_mtr_x'] = 10000*(base.angular_velocity_x/100*0.001)/base.acceleration_x
base['rad_per_mtr_y'] = 10000*(base.angular_velocity_y/100*0.001)/base.acceleration_y
base['rad_per_mtr_z'] = 10000*(base.angular_velocity_z/100*0.001)/base.acceleration_z
In [26]:
# Tackling Inf/NA values by replacing them by 0
base[['rad_per_mtr_x','rad_per_mtr_y','rad_per_mtr_z']] = base[['rad_per_mtr_x','rad_per_mtr_y','rad_per_mtr_z']].\
        replace([np.Inf,-np.Inf,np.nan],0)
base[['rad_per_mtr_x','rad_per_mtr_y','rad_per_mtr_z']].isin([np.Inf,-np.Inf,np.nan]).sum()

In [31]:
var1 = []; var2 = []
for i in range(len(cor_mat.columns)):
    for j in range(len(cor_mat.index)):
        if (cor_mat.iloc[i,j] > 0.65) & (i>j):
            var1.append(cor_mat.columns[i]); var2.append(cor_mat.index[j])
high_cor_var = list(zip(var1,var2))
